  <div class="page-content">
    <h1>{page.h1}</h1>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>If you have spent any amount of time observing the financial markets, you have likely seen headlines announcing that a major, well-known company is undergoing a "stock split." The financial media often covers these events with breathless excitement, treating them as massive, market-moving developments. But beneath the hype and the flashing red and green numbers on the ticker tape, what is a stock split, fundamentally?</p>

      <p>Imagine you have an entire pizza sitting in front of you. It is cut into four massive, unwieldy slices. You decide that four slices are simply too big to manage easily, so you take a pizza cutter and slice each of those four pieces perfectly in half. You now have eight slices of pizza. The slices are smaller, yes, but do you have more actual pizza than you did a moment ago? No. The total amount of food remains exactly identical. All you have done is change how the total mass is divided.</p>

      <p>This simple analogy perfectly encapsulates the core mechanic of a stock split. In the stock market, a company is the pizza, and the shares of stock are the slices. When a stock splits, the company is simply cutting its existing equity into a larger number of smaller pieces.</p>

      <p>In this comprehensive guide, we are going to dive deep into the mechanics of stock splits. We will explore exactly what happens to your portfolio when a split occurs, examine real-world historical examples, understand the psychological factors that drive companies to make these decisions, and learn how to navigate both forward and reverse splits as an informed investor.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h2>Defining the Core Concept: Forward Stock Splits</h2>
      <p>A standard stock split, often referred to as a forward stock split, is a corporate action in which a publicly traded company intentionally increases the total number of its outstanding shares while simultaneously decreasing the price of each individual share by the exact same proportion.</p>
      <p>The most crucial concept to internalize here is that a stock split has absolutely zero impact on the overall market capitalization (the total market value) of the company. It also has zero impact on the total value of the investment held by an individual shareholder. The underlying fundamentals of the business—its revenue, its profits, its debt, its assets—are entirely unaffected by the stroke of a pen that executes a stock split.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>How Does a Stock Split Actually Work?</h2>
      <p>To understand the mechanics of a stock split, it is best to look at the mathematical reality behind the event. When a company's board of directors announces a split, they establish a specific ratio. The most common ratios are 2-for-1 (written as 2:1), 3-for-1 (3:1), or occasionally larger ratios like 10-for-1 or even 20-for-1.</p>

      <h3>The Mathematical Breakdown</h3>
      <p>Let us construct a hypothetical scenario to see the math in action. Imagine a company called "Alpha Innovations." The stock is currently trading at $500 per share, and you are holding exactly 10 shares in your brokerage account.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Your Pre-Split Position:</strong> You own 10 shares at $500 each. Your total investment value is $5,000.</li>
        <li><strong>The Announcement:</strong> Alpha Innovations announces a 5-for-1 stock split. This means that for every 1 share an investor currently holds, they will magically have 5 shares after the split is executed.</li>
        <li><strong>The Price Adjustment:</strong> Because the total number of shares in existence is multiplying by 5, the price of each individual share must be divided by 5 to keep the total value of the company balanced. So, the $500 share price is divided by 5, resulting in a new share price of $100.</li>
        <li><strong>Your Post-Split Position:</strong> Your original 10 shares are multiplied by 5, giving you 50 shares. The new share price is $100. If you multiply your 50 shares by the $100 price, your total investment value is exactly $5,000.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>You have five times as many shares, but each share is worth exactly one-fifth as much. Your slice of the corporate pie has not grown; it has merely been cut into more pieces. You are no wealthier than you were before the split took place.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>Historical Examples of Massive Stock Splits</h2>
      <p>To put this into historical context, let's look at some of the most famous stock splits in recent market history. During the massive bull run of the late 2010s and early 2020s, several technology behemoths saw their share prices skyrocket into the thousands of dollars, prompting massive splits.</p>

      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Company</th>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Split Ratio</th>
              <th>Approximate Pre-Split Price</th>
              <th>Approximate Post-Split Price</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Apple (AAPL)</td>
              <td>2020</td>
              <td>4-for-1</td>
              <td>$500</td>
              <td>$125</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Tesla (TSLA)</td>
              <td>2020</td>
              <td>5-for-1</td>
              <td>$2,200</td>
              <td>$440</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
